							<h1>Why Give Dhamma Service?</h1>
							<p>Dhamma Ku&ntilde;ja is your center. It is here for you, and managed by old student volunteers like you. As students benefit from their own practice, the volition to see others benefit arises. This is how the center is able to exist - with the enthusiasm and dedication of old students.  Many students continue to find that serving at the center is an excellent way to deepen their practice and learn how to apply Vipassana in daily life.</p>
						</div>
						<div class="contentStory" >
							<h1>Ways of serving at the center</h1>
							<p>Please visit the <a href="http://courses.dhamma.org/schedules/schkunja">Course Schedule</a> or contact the <a href="mailto:dhamma-service@kunja.dhamma.org">Dhamma Service Committee</a> for more information about any of the following service opportunities.</p>
							<h2>Course service</h2>
							<p>Servers are always needed for courses. Servers clean, prepare food, and assist students as needed. In addition to ten-day courses, servers are needed for the monthly one-day courses.</p>
						</div>
						
						<div class="contentFeatureBox" >
							<div class="wrapper" >
								<img src="../Images/contentFeatureBox_Top.gif" border="0" align="top" alt="header"/>
								<div class="content" >
									<h1>Center Management Help Wanted</h1>
									<p>Dhamma Ku&ntilde;ja is looking for long-term servers to be part of a center management team.  As the center grows, so does the workload. We are seeking two or three old students for this team.  Responsibilities will be divided two or three ways, most likely to oversee kitchen/household; Dhamma service and training; and office management/communication.</p>
                		            <p>We would like to hear from you if you have the following qualifications: significant course service, 21 years of age or older, and available for one year or longer. Ideally, you have sat a long course or are eligible for a long course. Please reply by email to <a href="mailto:dhamma-service@kunja.dhamma.org">dhamma-service@kunja.dhamma.org</a> and someone will be in contact with you.</p>
                                </div>
								<img src="../Images/contentFeatureBox_Bottom.gif" border="0" align="top" alt="footer"/>
							</div>
						</div>
						
						<div class="contentStory" >
                            <h2>Serving between courses</h2>
							<p>Old students can come to the center to help with cleaning, laundry, maintenance, gardening, and other projects between courses (Sunday - Wednesday). Help is particularly need on day 0 (Wed.) and day 11 (Sun.) of each course.</p>
							<a name="SvcPeriod"></a>
							<h2>Service periods</h2>
							<p>Service periods are set aside a few times a year to work on larger maintenance, construction, household, and gardening projects. The daily program includes three group sittings with morning and afternoon work periods. On selected evenings, tapes of special discourses and talks given by Goenkaji are played. See sidebar for upcoming service period dates.</p>
							<h2>Old Students&rsquo; Service Weekends</h2>
							<p>These service weekends take place in the middle of a service period and include a more full and structured program including a guided center tour and opportunities to attend committee and trust meetings. See the <a href="OldStudentWeekend.html">Old Student Service Weekend</a> page for more information about these weekends.</p>
							<h2>Serving at other Dhamma Centers</h2>
							<p>The <a href="http://service.na.region.dhamma.org/" target="_blank">North American Service site</a> is available for old students interested in opportunities to serve at locations throughout the U.S. and Canada.</p>							
							<center><hr style="margin-top:20px; width:60%;"/></center>
							<h1>Serving in local communities</h1>
							<h2>Committees</h2>
							<p>Much of the planning and oversight of Vipassana activities in the Northwest is done by old students working on committees. These include Center Development, Center Management, Household, Kitchen, Landscaping, Outreach, Website, Maintenance, and Registration. All old students are welcome to join committees.</p>
							<h2>Local Outreach</h2>
							<p>You can help spread awareness of Vipassana in your community by posting literature about Vipassana or helping coordinate public events. You can start by downloading a <a href="docs/NVC_NS_SchedulePoster.pdf" target="_blank">Course Schedule poster</a> and posting it in your area. You can also apply to host monthly information sessions or a weekly group sitting for old students.</p>
